!TITLE
PREPARING FOR THE LEGAL STORM
!WORDS
  ª"Lawyers and judges, like the rest of society, have become 
increasingly secular and tend to look upon churches as 'just another 
business.'"´

   As our society becomes more secularized, churches can expect to 
face legal action that threatens the very heart of biblical ministry. 
Churches have been sued for not hiring job applicants with immoral 
lifestyles.  Some have been denied control over use of their 
facilities. Others have found themselves in counseling malpractice 
suits as lawyers and judges increasingly put the local church in the 
same category with businesses.
   çEmployment.  New laws protecting employability"rights" have 
serious implications for the church. In 1991, Hawaii enacted a 
homosexual rights law which specifically exempted churches, but only 
regarding the hiring of ministerial staff. Secretaries, janitors, 
even teachers are not exempt.  While Christians work together to 
change the laws, churches must prepare for confrontation.
   To protect your church, develop a written employment policy, 
specifying spiritual qualifications for every position in the church, 
including written justification for these qualifications.  It must be 
clear that any employee who evidences a rejection of the stated 
spiritual principles is subject to immediate termination.
   çCounseling malpractice.  Lawyers motivated by greed or hatred can 
use material from the American Bar Association to target churches and 
denominations for malpractice suits. Attorney Shelby Sharpe calls 
this the coming "nuclear attack" against churches.  Grace Community 
Church, pastored by John MacArthur, was the target of a highly 
publicized case wherein church counselors were charged with 
malpractice when a young man who had been counseled a number of years 
took his own life.  The church won in court, but at a cost in time 
and money that would bankrupt most congregations.
   What can you do?  Obtain liability insurance that covers clergy or 
counseling malpractice. Develop a form to be signed by every person 
coming to be counseled, stating that the counseling is spiritual, not 
psychological or psychiatric in nature.  Good notes should be kept of 
every session, with strict confidentiality maintained.
   çRestrictions on property use.  Zoning laws, while originally 
intended to benefit the general populace, now promote artificial 
inflation on land zoned for churches.  In some areas there is no land 
zoned for churches, requiring them to apply for special exemption, 
which results in thousands of dollars in legal fees. One Minnesota 
church was effectively denied a permanent location because the city 
refused to grant an exception to the zoning code.
   Taxation of church property is coming.  The U.S. Supreme Court has 
already laid the groundwork.  We have only to wait until politicians 
get desperate enough for money to brave the outcry from churches.
   The best way to combat such laws is by prevention.  Encourage some 
of your church members to serve in state and local governments, 
relieving them of other church responsibilities so that they can 
perform their work and family duties well.
     "Preparing for the legal storm" by Michael Farris. Ministries 
Today, Mar/Apr 1993.  Pages 70- 78.  Topic: CHURCH LAWSUITS.  See 
also 8610 and 7651.
